with [b, p].%0a%3c %0a%3c 3. labing-apat [la.biŋ.a.pat], number 14. %3clabing + apat> where apat is four and labing means +10, similar to how -teen works in fourteen. Notice the ng [ŋ] does not assimilate for vowels. It also applies to other consonants that do not fall under the same place of articulation as [n] or [m].%0a%3c %0a%3c As you can see from the examples, the place of articulation of the succeeding sound causes an assimilation of the last sound of the prefix. This makes sense because when the prefix is attached to the root word, it may be quite difficult to pronounce the velar nasal and immediately switch to an alveolar or bilabial consonant. Meanwhile, take an assimilation to [n] for example. If the succeeding consonant is [t], then the speaker would simply have to raise their velum to block the nasal cavity (the tongue does not move).%0a%3c %0a%3c This phenomenon is quite interesting due to its prevalence. While the occurrences shown above are taught in a formal setting, native speakers of Tagalog/Filipino naturally assimilate nasal consonants when speaking quickly. For example: Ang tagal mo! [aŋ ta.gal mɔ] "You're too slow!" when spoken naturally would instead sound like Antagal mo! [an.ta.gal mɔ]. This works for many other phrases, like "ang dilim" => "andilim" which is "it's so dark" and even in swear words (which I will not list here).%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
